<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-452-717  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 452 717.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 24 1990 v24 n39 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Split vote on advanced-tech groups. (companies create specialgroups to investigate new technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corporations seem undecided as to the value of maintainingseparate advanced technology research groups within a firm orwithin a company's information systems department.andP;  One poll of 75corporations shows that about half of them have formal advancedtechnology groups whose purpose is to investigate upcomingtechnologies that could benefit the company.andP;  At Ashland Oil Inc,the group looks at technologies that are about two years away frombecoming commercially viable.andP;  Involving business units with theprocess of technology analysis and acquisition is a goal of somesuccessful advanced technologies groups.andP;  Some companies encouragemembers of their information services groups to keep abreast ofemerging technologies instead of creating a separate group forthat purpose.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashland Oil Inc. (research).andO;Ticker:    ASH.andO;Topic:     CompaniesResearch and DevelopmentHigh TechnologyInformation servicesIndustry AnalysisSurvey.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Corporate interest in advanced technologies. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>